		<P CLASS="a0 b0 justify">
Thayer's Note: No.
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
The word, originally denoting a type of dancer, almost invariably means an effeminate male who engages in homosexual acts, especially as the passive partner in sodomy (Gell. <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Gellius/3*.html#5
	"TARGET="Gellius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.5</A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Gellius/6*.html#12
	"TARGET="Gellius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN>.12</A>;
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Suetonius/12Caesars/Augustus*.html#68
	"TARGET="Suetonius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LPlusE,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Suet. <I>Aug.</I> 68</A>;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/catullus.shtml
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Catullus, <I>passim</I> (esp. 16, 25, 29)</A>; Firmicus Maternus, (very frequently: Books <A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Firmicus_Maternus/Mathesis/7*.html
	"TARGET="Firmicus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN></A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Firmicus_Maternus/Mathesis/8*.html
	"TARGET="Firmicus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN></A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Firmicus_Maternus/Mathesis/3*.html
	"TARGET="Firmicus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN></A>,
	<A HREF="
L/Roman/Texts/Firmicus_Maternus/Mathesis/6*.html
	"TARGET="Firmicus"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<SPAN CLASS="small">VI</SPAN></A>). By a natural association, the word also migrated to a species of fish: Mair's note on Oppian
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Oppian/Mair_Introduction*/4.html#Alphestes_et_al
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Halieutica</I>, Introduction, p. l)
	</A>
is instructive.
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
What this particular <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">cinaedus</SPAN> was doing with a female prostitute is a bit of mystery — maybe she was a source of income, or a confidante in a marginal world — but there's no accounting for tastes. As for Cleomachus, there's plenty of kink to go around. His literary work recorded the gay cant of his time: a pity it's lost.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note63" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref63
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">63</A>
One who played the cithara and sang to its accompaniment (<I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/9C*.html#3.10
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">9.3.10 and note on "the citharoedes"</A>).


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note64" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref64
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">64</A>
City-Saviour.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note65" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref65
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">65</A>
<I>Odyssey</I> 9.3.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note66" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref66
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">66</A>
<I>i.e.</I> as <SPAN CLASS="Greek inscription caps">ΑΥΔΗ</SPAN> or <SPAN CLASS="Greek inscription caps">ΑΥΔΗΙ</SPAN>.

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
Thayer's Note: the subscript iota — which in the capital letters of inscriptions is written out as a full letter — had long been silent.
	</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note67" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref67
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">67</A>
12.<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#3.29
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">3.29</A>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#3.31
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">31</A>, <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/12C*.html#3.37
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">37</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note68" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref68
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">68</A>
The text, which seems to be corrupt, is recast and emended by Groskurd to read, "having crossed the Mesogis


<A ID="p261x"></A>towards the region to the south of Tmolus." But the simple rectification of the text made by the present translator solves the difficulty quite as well (see critical note).

	<DIV CLASS="mynote">
	<P CLASS="b0 a0 justify italic">
The critical note to the Greek text (<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ὑπερβᾶσι Τμῶλον καὶ τὸ ὄρος τὴν Μεσωγίδα ἐπὶ τὰ πρὸς τὸν νότον</SPAN>) reads:
		<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
<SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">καί</SPAN>, before <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τὸ ὄρος</SPAN>, Jones inserts. <SPAN CLASS="manuscript">E</SPAN> reads <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">τὸ ὄρος καὶ τὴν Μεσωγίδα</SPAN>.
	</P></DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note69" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref69
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">69</A>
<I>i.e.</I> meadow.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note70" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref70
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">70</A>
Apparently an error for "in which name the letter <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">omega</SPAN> is shortened to <SPAN CLASS="translit_Greek">omicron</SPAN><SPAN CLASS="emend">"</SPAN><!-- printed text omits closing quote --> (cp. the well-known Greek word Arōma, which may mean either "spice" or "arable land").<!-- the printed text puts the period inside the quotes -->



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:no_good_wine_in_Samos" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref:no_good_wine_in_Samos
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
The particle <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">δ’</SPAN> that articulates this clause to what precedes can often enough be left untranslated, but the word "Ampelus" in the preceding sentence means "grape-vine": it would have been better to translate "<I>Yet</I> the island does not produce good wine".


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:colophon" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref:colophon
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
Smacks of folk-etymology, but just the same, it's the origin of our word <SPAN CLASS="source">colophon</SPAN>, as in the printer's mark at the end of a book.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Massalia" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/14A*.html#ref:Massalia
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
Strabo's passage on Massalia (Massilia) is in
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Strabo/4A*.html#1.4
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
4.1.4‑5</A>; Phocaea is mentioned there, but only incidentally in connection with the founding of her colony. Nowhere in the <I>Geography</I> does Strabo describe Phocaea.



